summary:
Navy officer, university professor, historian, deputy in the National Assembly, colonial administration official and researcher, Avelino Teixeira da Mota left a vast body of work that encompasses the most varied areas of knowledge.  His research on history of cartography, Portugal-Africa relations, and on the discoveries and the history of navigation, resulted in a large and remarkable academic and scientific production.


Translated with www.DeepL.com/Translator (free version)
KEY WORDS:
Science; History of Cartography; 
Historiography; Empire; Navy; 
Colonial.

This paper wishes to analyse the attitude of importing objects used in daily life and related to food preparation and consumption such as tableware and kitchenware in areas which had been recently conquered or in where the European expansion had just started. Certainly these objects are a clear sign of cultural identity and self-representation. If we consider Ceuta, the shift in material culture before and after 1415 if evident. After the Portuguese conquest, and later on when Ceuta became a Spanish town, such objects continued to be imported from the Iberian Peninsula, coexisting with imports from different areas of the Mediterranean as well as with some objects of local production. This paper wishes to analyse the following issues:
-	Kitchenware imported from Portugal from 1415 onwards and probably still imported in the 17th century;
-	Tableware imported from different areas of the Mediterranean that was not in use in Ceuta and in the Iberian Peninsula only. These objects, in some cases with specific functional features (i.e. tin-glazed drinking cups imitating Chinese porcelain) were rather common in the Mediterranean area as well in the colonies of the New World from the 15th century onwards, responding to what we could consider a process of 'globalisation of taste', following the new routes of the global trade in the era of exploration;
-	The role of identity and self-representation in the attitude of selecting imports, comparing Ceuta and other Portuguese premises in Northern Africa with the colonies in the New World.
